{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_alicorn_ver02/data/sn89077295/00517010698/1957120701/0038.xml":{"full_text":"Page 4\nHf r I\nPublished Every Thuraday\nBy Herald Publishing Co.\n808 Montgomery Street\nTelephone: Dial AD 2-4505\nRemittance must be made by Express, Post Office\nMoney Order or Registered Mail.\nSecond Class Mail Privilege authorized at\nSavannah, Ga.\nNational Advertising Representative, Interstate\nUnited Newspapers, 545 Fifth Avenue, New York\n17, New York. Branch Office: 5 East Jackson\nBoulevard, Chicago, 111.\nNo guarantee of publication of unsolicited material.\nLetters to the editor on either side of any subject\nare welcomed, but must be signed and confined to\n250 words. No letters can be returned.\nFLOYD ADAMS Editor and Publisher\nMRS. W. A. ADAMS Assistant to Publisher\nA. A. MASON Associate Editor\nLUCIUS (\u201cKelly\u201d) BRYANT, SR.\nAdvertising Manager\nSUBSCRIPTION RATEFIN ADVANCE\nSix Months $3.00\nOne Year $4.00\nPRESIDENT\u2019S ILLNESS GETS\nSTRENGTH FROM NIXON\nToday the nation and the world is focused\non the illness of President Eisenhow\u2019er. A\nnation prayerfully hoping for recovery of its\nchief executive is concerned as to its status\nin world leadership while his health is im\npaired. The world considering the nation\u2019s\ndecision which rest on the shoulders of a\nonce virile leader that has shown a gradual\ndecline in health over a long period of time.\nThe assurance given the nation by the\nPresident several months ago that the\nduties of state would not go neglected has\ngiven the people added confidence in the ad\nministration despite condition relating to\nhealth. The President once stated, \u201cthere\ndent of the United States, when I feel I can\u2019t\nwill be no neglect in the duties of the Presi\ncarry them on I won\u2019t be there.\u201d A nation\nbelieving in the President\u2019s ability to think\nclearly would assume that should there be\nany impairment in the President\u2019s ability to\ndecide for its best interest feels that such\ndecisions would readily be placed in the\nhands of other capable persons.\nWhen we consider the President\u2019s medical\nhistory we find cause for much concern\nabout his health at this time complicated by\ntwo previous attacks during his service as\nPresident plus the advanced age of 67 and\nthe heavy responsibilities of office, we can\nnot predict a fast recovery to normal as we\nwould like to do, nor could we say whether\nthe duties of the president, now a strong fac\ntor in world politics should be delegated to\nsome other person or branch of government.\nThe nation concerned with the health of the\nY.M.C.A. This\nWeek\nThe officers of the George W.\nDe\u00dfenne Elementary School Gra-\nY and Tri-Gra-Y clubs were in\nstalled by George W. Williams,\nand assisted by Mrs. Rebecca E.\nMitchell, Youth Secretaries of the\nWest Broad Street Y.M.C.A. Jo\nseph R. Jenkins, Executive Secre\ntary, spoke on \u201cY.M.C.A. World\nService.\u201d Thanksgiving gift pack\nages were on hand to be distrib\nuted to the needy for Thanksgiv\ning. Mrs. Grace Jenkins and Mrs.\nDrucilla Hargrett are the club ad\nvisers, and Mrs. E. S. Warrick is\nthe principal of the school.\nA Thanksgiving program was\ngiven by the Tri-Gra-Y club of\nthe Frank W. Spencer Elementary\nSchool, where gift packages were\nturned over to the Chatham Coun-\nty Department of Welfare for dis\ntribution to the needy. Mrs. Lois\nDotson is the club adviser, Mrs.\nAyler Mae Lovett, is the princi\npal of Frank W. Spencer School.\nM. 0. Johnston, member of the\nBoard of Management of the West\nBroad Street Y.M.C.A., and a\nmember of the Southern Area\nCouncil of Y.M.C.A.s committee on\nWorld Service, will go to Atlanta\nFriday to attend the meeting of\nthis committee. Johnston has\nserved a three-year term on the\nArea Board of Directors, This\nmeeting will be held at the Luckie\nStreet Y.M.C.A. He will chairman\nthe group that will go out for\nadult participation in Y.M.C.A.\nWorld Service and Buildings for\nBrotherhood during 1958.\nThe \u201cCoronation Ball\u201d which\nwill wind up the \u201cMost Popular\nY. Lady\u201d member contest will\nbe staged Friday, December 6, at\nthe Flamingo Ball room, from\n10:00 to 2:00 P. M. The music will\nPresident personally is also taking a view\nat the mental and physical strain that will\ncontinue to draw on his energies during the\ncurrent time when executive decision is such\ngreat factor.\nThere have been many causes for uncer\ntainty in the present illness of the President\nas it was referred to as a chill. The people\nare remembering the heart attack suffered\nby the President that was first referred to\nas to a digestive upset and the subsequent\nIleitis attack that was first spoken of as up\nset stomach and headache. This kind of un\ncertainty is also evident in business trends\nand foreign relations. These phenomena are\nclosely related to any statement concerning\nthe President\u2019s health and we advocated de\npendable information being legally dispatch\ned to the American public in order that they\nmay be prepared to face the multitude chal\nlenge that follows such news.\nIhe question primarily in the minds of\nmany persons is the prospect of the Presi\ndent\u2019s illness lasting once any extended\nperiod. With so many things coming up that\nwill demand executive decision and national\nprestige it is constantly being asked if Presi\ndent Eisenhower should not delegate the\nduties of the President to the vice president.\nIn the past periods of illness this was not\nsuggested. It seemed that the nation was\nreluctant to trust its destinies in the hands\nof the young vice president. Today that feel\ning has been replaced, it is believed that\nVice President Nixon has grown in statute\nin both national and international affairs.\nThe supporters of both parties agree that\nthe office of President would be greatly en\nhanced by the vice president in case of any\nemergency that would require his services as,\nsuch. It is fortunate however that the Presi\ndent is still able to make his own decision\nbut should the emergency arise it is also for\ntunate that we have a vice president better\ntrained than any before him to carry out the\nduties and tasks of the presidency. This is\nindeed cause for increased faith of a people\nthat has readied itself to withstand the shock\n\u2022of any changes necessary.\nFollowing the first illness of the President\nmany attempts have been made to create\nlaws that will relieve the President of his\n\u2022duties in case of illness. Congressional com\nmittees have studied several plans but no\none has come up with an answer that will\nreplace the constitutional provision already\nin effect. The Constitution provides for the\nvice president to assume the duties of exec\nutive office if the President is incapicitated\nas to \u201cinability to discharge the powers and\nduties\u201d of President this clause has never\nbeen clearly defined. The only other reason\nfor the vice president assuming such au\nthority is resignation.\nThe nation prays for the Tull aM com\nplete recovery of our President and as it\ndoes the situation is not relieved by the many\nduties and responsibilities which mav tend\nto make recovery more difficult. The need\nfor legislation to delegate the President\u2019s\nnowers may seem important, but beyond this\nthe nation recognizes the importance of a\nstrong presidential team which means lead\nership regardless of emergency. Today\u2019s\nteam features a man who of his own admis\nsion will step down and a man in reserve\nthat has shown his ability to serve.\nTHE HERALD\nbe furnished by James Drayton\nan.l his Combo. The following\nlad^s are being featured this year\nin the contest that will Tmlp the\nWest Broad Street Y.M.C.A. end\nits year free of debt. A shower\nof gifts will be given to the win\nning lady by interested friends\nof the local association. The con\ntestants are: Miss Francis John\nson, Mrs. Lillian Scott, Miss Dor\nris D. Williams, Mrs. M. A. Hull,\nMrs. Lois Dotson, Mrs. Sara Van-\nEllison, Miss Phoen Sinclair, Miss\nRuth Mullino, Miss Cleo Wilker\nson, Miss Johnny Mitchell.\nThe weekly USO dance for serv\nicemen will be held at the Y Sat\nurday night beginning at 8:30\nP.M. Mrs. Francis J. Johnson,\nUSO Staff Aide will be in charge.\nAll servicemen are invited to at\ntend.\nUsually, when these two get to\ngether with 3 bongo players there\u2019s\nTHE AMERICAN WAY\nw (WEIGHT* A 1\nz X I YOU\u2019VE 60T IS IJi\nbuttm I WIUTISIY/ J\nI entitled TO A ,1\nI RIGHT TO WOtK//\nj. I i\n^IIW Mi-\nMaking Second-Class Citizens\nNAVY\u2019S \u201cFASTEST\u201d\u2019\nThe U- S. Reina; Mercedes,\nformer Spanish cruiser,, known as\nthe Navy\u2019s \u201cfastest\u201d ship because\nshe was tied fast to a. Naval\nAcademy dock for 45 years, is\nheaded for the scrap heap:. The\nNavy ruled she had outlived\u2019 her\nusefulness and cost too, much; to\nkeep repaired. It had been used\nfor* training and for barracks for\nnaval plebes.\nFREAK ACCIDENT\nLos Angeles, Calif.\u2014While fish\ning with his father, Don Lyon;. 15-\nyear-old boy, threw a heavy anchor\nfrom their cabin cruiser. The rope\nattached ta. the anchor' was- coiled\naround Don\u2019s leg and he was\npulled into 45 feet of water. The\nrope was not secured to the boat\nand the boy drowned before he\ncould be rescued.\nDIES IN FATHER\u2019S ARMS\nGlenwood Springs, Colo. A\nfather, Junior Scott, and his 8-\nyear-old son, Richard Leroy, went\nhunting in the mountains. Unsuc\ncessful in their attempt to find a\ntrail down from the shale rimrocks\nin the dark, they were forced to\nremain in the mountains overnight\nwith the temperature in the mid\ndle 20\u2019s. The father held the boy\nagainst his own body in an effort\nto keep him warm, but the child\nfroze to death before rescuers\nfound them.\nOLD DEBT REPAID\nPittsburgh Mrs. Harper H.\nSmith, now 80, recently received\n$24 for damages to her car\u2014which\nhad been broken into by four\nyouths in 1937. The delay was ex\nplained by Clerk of Court Thomas\nE. Barret who said that about\n5,000 restitution cases were re\ncently transferred to his office\nfrom the county probation office.\nMrs. Smith\u2019s was among those in\nthe transfer.\nNews Report\nFrom Washington\nSaturday, December 7, 1957\nleft hih .nm.\nDenver; Colo \u2014Jose- Salazar,.\nhelping clear a site for a; new high\nschool building;, loaded: a truck\nwith tree trunks and branches and\nheaded for the city dump. En\nroute, his shifting load scratched\nand dented almost every car\nparked on the right-hand side of\nthe streets along the route. Along\nthe 2-mile trip, more than 50 cars\nwere damaged.\nCIGARETTES.\nIt is likely that Americans will\nconsume about fifteen per cent\nmore cigarettes in 1965 than this\nyear, according to the Agriculture\nDepartment. But the use of tobacco\nin making cigarettes may not in\ncrease more than five per cent,\nit said. This is because more and\nmore of the tobacco stem is being\nused in cigarettes than in the past\nINCOMES DROP.\nThe Commerce Department has\nreported that factory layoffs and\nreduced working time caused a\n11,000,000,000 drop in the annual\nrate of personal income in October.\nThe October reduction and a $2OO,\n000,000 September decline marked\nthe first time U. S. personal in\ncome had declined for two succes\nsive months since the Spring of\n1954. Personal income statistisc re\npresent the total wage, salary,\ndividend, pension and other pay\nments to individuals.\nFOOD DONATIONS DROP.\nA total of 490,800,000 pounds of\nsurplus foods were given away in\nthis country and abroad from July\nthrough September. The food, valu\ned at $86,200,000, went to schools\nneedy persons and institutions in\nthis country and to disaster vic\ntims overseas. However, this was\na 30.5 per cent drop from such\ndonations from the same period\nin 1956.","height":"27728","width":"17683"}}
